column168: At 1110 on 07 Sep 2017 ERTS was notified by Joy Hawthorne of XPO in Alabama about a spill that occurred at 0730 on 07 Sep 2017. The product spilled was Drain Klean. column168: On September 7, 2017,  XPO Logistics XHG1 reported 50-gallons of NA1760, Compounds, Cleaning, Liquid (Contains: Hydrofluoric Acid), 8, PGIII, trade name Rage Plus, released from (1) 55-gallon poly drum. The reported cause of the release was improper loading, the drum was punctured by a nail on the pallet. The drum is located at the nose of the trailer and freight is still reportedly on the trailer that will need to be offloaded. The release has impacted the trailer floor, concrete dock. An estimated 5-gallons of material has impacted the concrete beneath the trailer. The contractor stated the release has impacted a 15' x 2' area and the asphalt yard, tracked from the trailer across 20' x 1' of the concrete dock, and the trailer floor. Approximately 40 gallons of product was released. Contractor utilized sodium bicarbonate to clean and neutralize the release. Contractor generated   (1) 95-gallon poly over pack containing the (1) 55-gallon poly drum of Rage Plus. Estimated 10 gallons remaining  (5) 55-gallon poly drums containing neutralized absorbent pads, cut up pallet, and PPE. All waste staged on site for XPO to manage disposition.

All waste was staged on site for XPO to manage disposition.

column168: At 0842 on 11Sep2017  Daniel Tu with XPO Logistics in Minnesota called to report a spill of 2 1/2 to 3 gallons of UN 3077 Copper Sulfate. The spill occurred after a 2000 pound super sack tore while removing from the trailer to the dock.  SDS  was reviewed with Mr. Tu over the phone. Advised that there could be a dust hazard if a dust cloud was formed. Advised Mr. Tu that we could either dispatch a contractor for clean-up or he could attempt to clean it up himself without creating a dust cloud. He advised that he felt comfortable cleaning it up himself. Product was swept up and placed into a 40 gallon steel drum.  Cargo was on Trailer #XTRA13029. Wenck Associates responded to the spill. They cleaned out a 40 gallon steel drum that had Copper Sulfate in it. Placed impacted debris and the copper sulfate into a 55 gallon poly drum.

column168: UTLX 679212 was noted as having residue on the outside of the tank car upon entering the yard.  Upon further inspection, it was noted that the leak was originating from the area between the tank car and the pressure plate assembly. A slight ammonia odor was also noticed off and on. No wetness or visible liquid leaks were visible, only dried heavy deposits of the product that extended from the protective housing toward the "B" end of the car. Lighter deposits were noted as dried down the side of the car, immediately below the protective housing assembly. The release is  estimated at 3 liquid gallons of product.  The car was moved to a track isolated from the rest of the yard. The BNSF HazMat manager further inspected the car and found that 31 of the 32 bolt/nut assemblies that secure the pressure plate housing to the tank car were less than tool tight. The bolts were secured to the best of on-site ability and the car secured, awaiting for transfer. The shipper is providing a residue car and a contractor will do a product transfer upon arrival of the residue car.
column169: Shipper needs to ensure that procedures for loading and proper packaging of the tank car are followed to prevent this type of hazardous materials release in the future.

The car was isolated and the shipper Nucor Corporation, the Georgia Environmental Protection Division (report number CTS 84018), and the NRC (report number 1189495) were notified.  CHEMTREC report number 2017-09-06-00007.  Hulls Environmental, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the car leaking from the air inlet.  The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper (Mike Kridner, phone number 843-336-6188).  Contractor personnel replaced the broken nut / bolt assembly.  The tank car lessee has arranged for a mobile repair unit to inspect and repair the damaged nut and bolt assembly.

column168: A Safety-Kleen employee was offloading a wrangler bag that was staged on a pallet which had a broken board from a box truck. column62: Inadequate Preparation for Transportation; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: When the FRA Hazmat Inspector was doing a routine inspection in the WLE Brewster Yard, they found tank car SHQX 50050 leaking from the A end liquid valve.  He called myself, John Vergis Environmental Officer for WLE to come out to the yard to look at the car.  When I investigated, i found that the A end liquid valve handle was loose.  I tightened the valve handle and the leak stopped.  I checked the valve plug and it was loose also, so i tightened it.  I removed seal FRA 36009 from the car but did not install a new one.            NARRI: 5(4+5)x2=47         Code:115,282
column169: Better car securement procedures need followed.

UPON ARRIVING TO THE SPILL, I SAW THE PACKAGE MARKED WITH A CORROSIVE (8) AND OXIDIZER (5.1) DIAMOND LABEL AND UPS HAZMAT SHIPPING PAPERS. I FOLLOWED THE RESPONSE ACTION STEPS AND TOOK THE PACKAGE BACK TO PSC AND REFERRED TO THE WASTE DISPOSAL CHART FOR FULL DMP FACILITY.  AFTER WHICH, I DECONTAMINATED MY PPE.

column42: PAINT RELATED MATERIAL INCLUDING PAINT THINNING, DRYING, REMOVING, OR REDUCING COMPOUND
column168: At 1414 EST, Terri Smith from XPO (XSL) contacted ERTS in regards to a UN1263 paint related material release that occurred at 1345 EST on 09/21/2017. It was reported that 0.5 gallon of material released from 1-5 gal pail to the trailer floor and impacted another 5 gal poly pail and the carton due to improper loading. Prior to contacting ERTS, terminal personnel used absorbents to clean the release. The impacted pails and absorbents were placed into a 85 gal metal drum and staged in the waste area. There were no drains, soils or waterways reported to have been impacted by the release. Spills in trailers, concrete docks, containment areas, inside buildings are not into environment and not considered reportable so there is no regulatory reporting required for this release. All waste was managed by terminal personnel.

Carrier at consignee off loading CTMV when carrier noticed product leaking from PTO shaft on carrier tractor. Carrier shut down pump and leaked stopped. Carrier found a weld cracked on the shaft connection of tractor which runs the pump for CTMV.     event  66150-1

Carrier at consignee off loading CTMV into totes and noticed the carrier tractor pump started leaking. Carrier shut down and the leak stopped. Carrier found the package on the front spindle shaft on pump blew out and was replaced.     event 66122-1

Carrier inspected loaded CTMV on site for shipment and found CTMV leaking at the external valve. Carrier inspected and found the outer clamp on valve was loose and tightened which stopped the leak.       event 66205-1

WHILE UNLOADING DISCOVERED DAMAGED AND LEAKING TOTE. CERTIFIED CONTRACTOR TRANSFERRED CONTENTS TO NEW TOTE. AWAITING DISPOSITION FROM THE SHIPPER. SPILLAGE MANAGED PROPERLY OTHER NON HAZ PORTION OF THIS SHIPMENT MOVING ON TO CONSIGNEE
column169: MANAGEMENT TO SPEAK WITH SHIPPER REGARDING THE RECURRING PACKAGING FAILURE ON THESE TOTES.

THE SHIPMENT DID NOT CONTAIN ANY HAZARD LABELS- UN #, ORIENTATION LABELS NOR UN BOX WAS USED. NO MSDS INCLUDED IN SHIPMENT.

column168: BNSF Yard personnel reported UTLX 201722 to be leaking from the combination housing at the top of the car on 9/1/17 at approximately 2000hrs.  Car was a load of STCC 4908177 Gasoline UN1203 class 3 flammable liquid.  BNSF hazmat dispatched contractor NRC Environmental Services out of Spokane, WA to inspect and repair the car.  Upon arrival NRC gained access to the protective housing and found a slow leak of liquid coming from the base of the liquid valve.  Further inspection revealed securement nuts at the base of the valve flange attaching it to the car were finger tight.  NRC properly tightened to a tool tight condition and checked all other valves and closures with no exceptions.  Leak was confined mainly to the skin of the car and was wiped clean.  No environmental remediation required.
column169: Ensure loading personnel are properly trained to prepare a hazmat container for shipment to include inspection of all securement, valves, primary, and secondary closure devices on the top and bottom of the car as required.  Conduct re-training and spot auditing as necessary.

column168: APPROXIMATELY 0240, JOSEPH KRUEGER WAS NOTIFIED THAT HE WAS REQUESTED TO REPORT TO THE DAMAGE CAGE FOR IMMEDIATE DESIGNATED RESPONDER DUTIES. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE DAMAGE CAGE APPROXIMATELY 2:45-2:55 JOSEPH WAS NOTIFIED BY KRISTY HARLAN THAT HE NEEDED TO RESPOND TO A HAZARDOUS WASTE SPILL AT THE IRREGULAR PACKAGE STATION, TO WHICH JOSEPH LEFT THE DMP AND UTILIZED THE SPILL CART SITUATED OUTSIDE OF P.E. TO RESPOND TO THE SPILL. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SCENE OF THE SPILL APPROXIMATELY 03:00, JOSEPH WAS POINTED TO A METAL 5 GALLON BUCKET SITTING ON AN IRREG CART WITH AN EXTREMELY SHALLOW AND SMALL PUDDLE AROUND THE BOTTOM RIMS OF THE BUCKET, TO WHICH HE SETUP A 15FOOT HOTZONE AND UTILIZED HIS DECISION TREE AND APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEETS TO FIRST DETERMINE THAT THE APPROPRIATE COURSE OF ACTION TO A CONFIRMED FLAMMABLE LIQUID 3.1 WHICH DID NOT PRODUCE IRRITATING FUMES OR VAPORS, WAS TO CONTINUE TO WEAR BASIC PPE, CLEAN UP ACCORDING TO THE CORRELATING RESPONSE SHEET, RETURN TO THE DMP, PROCESS SPILL, AND DECONTAMINATE.

PACKAGE WAS RECEIVED AT OUR SHIPPING DOCK FROM A CUSTOMER WITH A COCKPIT VOICE/DATA RECORDER (CVR) INSIDE THE PACKAGE. THE 90 DAY BEACON ON THE CVR CONTAINS 1.75G LITHIUM METAL CONTENT SO THIS WAS A LITHIUM METAL BATTERY PACKAGED IN EQUIPMENT SHIPMENT. PACKAGE HAD NO MARKINGS THAT IT WAS DANGEROUS GOOD/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SHIPMENT. OUR SHIPPING DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL UNPACK-AGED THE UNIT AND DELIVERED THE UNIT TO OUR REPAIR DEPARTMENT. WE NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER THEY SHIPPED A DANGEROUS GOOD WITHOUT THE PROPER LABELS AND DOCUMENTATION AND THAT THEY NEEDED TO REMEDY THIS IN THE FUTURE AND THAT UNIVERSAL AVIONICS WAS REQUIRED TO REPORT THE INCIDENT. THERE WAS NO RELEASE.
column169: OUR PERSONNEL HAVE RECEIVED TRAINING ON RECOGNIZING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS ARRIVING AT OUR DOCK WITH ISSUES AND TO NOTIFY MANAGEMENT WHEN AN INCIDENT OCCURS. WE PROVIDED ADDITIONAL TRAINING TO RECOGNIZE WHEN A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL ARRIVES WITHOUT THE APPROPRIATE MARKINGS OR DOCUMENTATION AND NO RELEASE AND TO IMMEDIATELY REPORT IT TO MANAGEMENT SO WE CAN CAPTURE ALL THE APPROPRIATE INFORMATION IN ORDER TO REPORT THE INCIDENT. WE HAVE ALSO NOTIFIED CUSTOMERS AND DEALERS THROUGH NEWSLETTERS, A NOTICE ON OUR CUSTOMER WEBSITE AND A SERVICE BULLETIN ABOUT RESHIPPING THIS PARTICULAR PRODUCT FOR REPAIRS AND THE NEED TO SHIP AS DANGEROUS GOODS/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.

column168: (2) 275 gallon poly totes containing UN2734 Amines were damaged during transportation after the two improperly secured totes struck the trailer wall. column168: On the date of the incident, a Hawaii Gas (HG) tanker truck driver was driving on a two-lane highway carrying approximately 1,500 gallons of propane in his 3,000-gallon capacity tanker (i.e., approximately 50% volume).  While driving south, an oncoming northbound SUV crossed the center-line and drove toward the shoulder of the HG driver's lane. To avoid a head-on collision, the HG driver steered left.  The front end of his bobtail clipped the front passenger side of the SUV, causing the tanker truck to roll over and land on its rooftop along the east side of the highway.  The SUV came to rest along the west side of the highway.  Damage to the piping on the back of the bobtail caused a propane leak, which ignited.     The fire department and Hawaii Gas responders determined that since the fire posed no immediate danger to life or property, the safest option was to let the fire burn and keep firefighting water on the vapor space of the tank to control the inner pressure.  The police and fire departments contained the situation and closed the highway for approximately 44 hours (it took approximately 39 hours for the propane to burn off).     Other than the damage to the tanker truck, all other property damage and personal injury suffered were caused by the impact of the traffic collision and were not related to the fire.  The HG driver sustained serious injuries from the collision and was transported to Hilo Medical Center for treatment.  The driver and rear seat passenger (child) of the SUV were uninjured.  However, the female occupant in the front passenger seat died at the scene of the accident.
column169: The police report for this incident indicated that the SUV driver was inattentive, which caused him to cross the center-line.  One possible solution may be for the County to add rumble strips to two-lane highways to alert inattentive drivers when they cross the center-line.

column168: At 1440 EST, Barry Wright from XPO (XMC) contacted ERTS in regards to a UN1263 Paint related material (flammable) release that occurred at 0200 EST on 09/25/2017. It was reported that 0.5 gallon of product released from 8- 5 gallon metal pails to the trailer floor due to blocking and bracing . There were no drains, soils or waterways reported to have been impacted by the release.Personnel terminal overpacked the impacted pails and absorbents into 3-55 gal metal drums. All waste was managed by terminal personnel.

column168: On September 19, 2017, at 1030 hours, DOT FRA Hazardous Material Inspector at the South Philadelphia, Pennsylvania Rail Yard took exception to UTLX 646149, a residue last contained tank car of UN1866, Resin Solutions. Reportedly there was product around the vacuum relief valve (VRV) and possible release of vapors. The tank car was placed on hazmat hold pending inspection by CSXT. The shipper, Ashland Incorporated, was notified via Chemtrec, report #2017091900118. Hepaco, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the South Philadelphia Yard along with a CSXT Hazardous Material Manager. It was found that the (VRV) was in fact open and slightly releasing vapor. There was visible product around and inside the valve. The VRV was removed and a plug was placed securely in its place. Prior to continuing in transportation a One Time Movement Approval was required to be obtained. The shipper representative, Alissa Wykes,  215.446.7911 was notified of the situation found. Ashland Incorporated received One Time Movement Approval to home shop the tank car.     NARRI: 2x(4+1+0)x(2+0) = 20  Cause code:1122

ON 9/7/2017 AT APPROXIMATELY 03:35AM LION OIL DRIVER REPORTED A LEAK COMING FROM THE TOP OF CARGO TANK UNIT 403. THE UNIT WAS LOADED WITH RED DYE DIESEL (OFF ROAD DIESEL) IN ROUTE TO HASLET, TX. THE CARGO TANKER IS A BOTTOM LOAD TANKER. AFTER LOAD COMPLETION UNIT 403 TRAVELED APPROXIMATELY .56 MILES WHEN THE DRIVER NOTICED THE PRODUCT ON THE OUTER SHELL OF CARGO TANKER 403. HE THEN IMMEDIATELY PULLED OVER AND CALLED INTO THE SAFETY DEPARTMENT. AFTER SAFETY ARRIVED IT WAS NOTICED THAT THE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED FROM THE CLEAN OUT PORTS. THE DESCRIPTION OF THE TANKER IS A SINGLE COMPARTMENT DOT407 DOUBLE CONICAL CARGO TANKER. THE UNIT HAS 4 CLEAN OUT PORTS EVENLY SPACED FROM FRONT TO BACK ON THE VERY TOP ALIGNED IN THE CENTER OF THE SHELL.   PRIOR TO BEING LOADED THE TRAILER WAS DOWN FOR REPAIRS AT A LOCAL 3RD PARTY VENDOR WHERE THE UNIT WAS INTERNALLY STEAMED OUT. AFTER THE STEAM OUT PROCESS THE CLEAN OUR PORT CLOSURES WERE NOT REINSTALLED. THE 3RD PARTY VENDOR CLEARED THE UNIT TO BE PUT BACK IN SERVICE AND DIDN’T REALIZE THE CAPS OF THE PORTS WERE NEVER REINSTALLED. THE CAPS, GASKETS, AND HARDWARE WAS FOUND STORED IN THE “CROW’S NEST” ON TOP OF THE TRAILER DURING OUR INTERNAL INVESTIGATION. THIS WAS NOT NOTICED BY THE DRIVER DUE TO THE TRAILER BEING A BOTTOM LOAD/UNLOADED AND THE COMPANY POLICY WHERE LION OIL DOES NOT ALLOW DRIVERS ON TOP OF CARGO UNITS WITHOUT FALL PROTECTION.   AS THE DRIVER OF CARGO TANKER UNIT 403 PROCEEDED IN HIS ROUTE EACH TIME HE WOULD ACCELERATE OR COME TO A SLOW/STOP THE SLOSH OF THE PRODUCT WOULD FORCE OUT OF THE CLEAN OUT PORTS THAT WERE OPEN ON TOP OF THE CARGO TANKER. DURING THIS EVENT PRODUCT RELEASED ONTO THE SMALL SECTION OF ROADWAY AT APPROXIMATELY 35 GALLONS. A LOCAL HAZMAT REMEDIATION COMPANY WAS CONTACTED AND CLEANUP STARTED WITHIN 2 HOURS.
column169: ACTIONS TAKEN TO PREVENT RECURRENCE: WE HAVE WORKED WITH LOCAL VENDOR TO DO A CHECK THROUGH ONCE A UNIT HAS BEEN RETURNED TO SERVICE TO PREVENT FUTURE RECURRENCES. IF THE UNIT IS NOT YET RETURNABLE TO SERVICE THE VENDOR WILL INSTALL A GLAD HAND LOCK ON THE SERVICE AIR SUPPLY TO KEEP THE UNIT FROM BEING OPERATED. THE VENDOR WILL ALSO INSTALL THE GLAD HAND LOCK IF THE UNIT IS STILL IN PROCESS OF BEING REPAIRED TO PREVENT THE UNIT FROM BEING OPERATED.  THE VENDOR WILL ALSO INSTALL THE GLAD HAND LOCK IF THE UNIT IS STILL IN PROCESS OF BEING REPAIRED TO PREVENT THE UNIT FROM BEING OPERATED. WE FEEL THIS IS MORE SECURE AND FAIL PROOF AND WILL REPLACE A SIMPLE “RED TAG”.

column168: DURING THE UNLOAD OF A TRAILER FOR THE PURPOSE OF CONSOLIDATING WASTE FOR SHIPMENT TO A FINAL DESTINATION, A FACILITY TECHNICIAN PICK UP THE DRUM IN QUESTION WITH A FORK LIFT, AND ITS TOP POPPED OFF, SPILLING 5 GALLONS OF WASTE MEK INTO THE VAN TRAILER, WHICH WAS POSITIONED IN CONTAINMENT. IT WAS LATER DETERMINED THE DRUM TOP AND CLOSURE WAS NOT CORRECTLY TIGHTENED. FACILITY PERSONNEL DONNED THE APPROPRIATE PERSONNEL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND TOOK IMMEDIATE STEPS TO CONTAIN THE SPREAD OF THE RELEASE AND TO PROTECT THE GROUND, SHOULD THE LIQUID WASTE SEEP THROUGH THE TRAILER FLOOR. THE RELEASE IMPACTED ONLY THE TRAILER; NO GROUND, SOIL, OR WATER SOURCES WERE IMPACTED. AN APPROPRIATELY TRAINED FIELD SERVICE RESPONSE CREW WAS SUMMONED, DONNED THE CORRECT PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT, PROPERLY INSTALLED THE DRUM TOP AND CLOSURE TO MANUFACTURER SPECIFICATIONS, AND OVER-PACKED THE DRUM INTO A CORRECTLY RATED SALVAGE OVER-PACK DRUM. THE TRAILER FLOOR WAS ALSO CLEANED THOROUGHLY.    THE WASTE GENERATED BY THE CLEANUP WAS PLACED INTO AN APPROPRIATE BRANCH WASTE STREAM FOR LATER DISPOSAL. THE OVER-PACKED DRUM WAS THEN TRANSFERRED WITHOUT INCIDENT TO ITS FINAL DESTINATION.    THIS RELEASE WAS REPORTED THE CT DEEP – SPILL CASE #2017-04467; OPERATOR #203.
column169: THE GENERATOR WAS INFORMED OF THE INCIDENT, AND ASKED TO GIVE THEIR EMPLOYEES ADDITIONAL TRAINING ON DRUM CLOSURE AND CONTAINER INSPECTION. THE DRIVER RESPONSIBLE FOR TRANSPORTING THIS DRUM WAS GIVEN ADDITIONAL CONTAINER DRUM CLOSURE AND INSPECTION TRAINING, WITH AN EMPHASIS ON THE REQUIREMENT TO CHECK ALL DRUM CLOSURES FOR PROPER INSTALLATION, CLOSURE BOLT TORQUE VALVES, AND JAMB NUT PLACEMENT.

column168: Carrier driver was in route to consignee when he noticed hazmat dripping from the drain tubes of the crashbox on the CMTV.  Driver discovered the vent valve in the crash box had leaked during transport.  The duration of the release occurred no longer than six hours.  The hazmat release ceases when the CTMV is at a stop and the liquid is no longer sloshing.  The driver parked on level ground and a cleanup crew was contacted.  The filter stone within the vent valve was found to be saturated from excessive sloshing of the product due to traffic and roadway grade.  Filter Stone was replaced onsite.       Quality Event #66021.

PACKAGE WAS RECEIVED AT OUR SHIPPING DOCK FROM A CUSTOMER WITH A COCKPIT VOICE/DATA RECORDER (CVR) INSIDE THE PACKAGE. THE 90 DAY BEACON ON THE CVR CONTAINS 1.75G LITHIUM METAL CONTENT SO THIS WAS A LITHIUM METAL BATTERY PACKAGED IN EQUIPMENT SHIPMENT. PACKAGE HAD NO MARKINGS THAT IT WAS A DANGEROUS GOODS/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SHIPMENT. OUR SHIPPING DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL UNPACKAGED THE UNIT AND DELIVERED THE UNIT TO OUR REPAIR DEPARTMENT.WE NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER THEY SHIPPED A DANGEROUS GOOD WITHOUT THE PROPER LABELS AND DOCUMENTATION AND THAT THEY NEEDED TO REMEDY THIS IN THE FUTURE AND THAT UNIVERSAL AVIONICS WAS REQUIRED TO REPORT THE INCIDENT. THERE WAS NO RELEASE.
column169: OUR PERSONNEL HAVE RECEIVED TRAINING ON RECOGNIZING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS ARRIVING AT OUR DOCK WITH ISSUES AND TO NOTIFY MANAGEMENT WHEN AN INCIDENT OCCURS. WE PROVIDED ADDITIONAL TRAINING TO RECOGNIZE WHEN A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL ARRIVES WITHOUT THE APPROPRIATE MARKINGS OR DOCUMENTATION AND NO RELEASE AND TO IMMEDIATELY REPORT IT TO MANAGEMENT SO WE CAN CAPTURE ALL THE APPROPRIATE INFORMATION IN ORDER TO REPORT THE INCIDENT. WE HAVE ALSO NOTIFIED CUSTOMERS AND DEALERS THROUGH NEWSLETTERS, A NOTICE ON OUR CUSTOMER WEBSITE AND A SERVICE BULLETIN ABOUT RESHIPPING THIS PARTICULAR PRODUCT FOR REPAIRS AND THE NEED TO SHIP AS DANGEROUS GOODS/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE EXITING A FACILITY THE TOTE TANK ROLLED OUT OF THE TRAILER DUE TO THE TRAILER DOOR NOT BEING PROPERLY SECURED. APPROXIMATELY 200 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND IMPACTED AN ASPHALT PARKING LOT SURFACE AND A DITCH LINE. THE WISCONSIN STATE POLICE AND THE WINNEBAGO COUNTY HAZMAT TEAM RESPONDED TO ASSESS THE SITE. CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES {CHES} WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. CHES ARRIVED AND INSPECTED THE SITE. CHES DISCOVERED A LARGE AREA OF IMPACTED GRAVEL ONTHE SHOULDER OF THE ROAD. CHES EMPTIED THE REMAINING PRODUCT FROM THE TOTE INTO TWO (2) 55-GALLON DRUMS. CHES PROCEEDED TO EXCAVATE THE CONTAMINATED SOIL FROM THE IMPACTED AREA. THE CONTAMINATED SOIL AND GRAVEL WERE PLACED INTO A ROLL-OFF BOX FOR DISPOSAL. CHES COORDINATED DISPOSAL OF THE WASTE GENERATED AS A RESULT OF THE INCIDENT.

column168: NOTIFIED BY DISTRICT REGULATED GOODS COORDINATOR, TO STOP THIS PACKAGE AFTER IT ARRIVED AT 6629. REQUESTED AN INTERCEPT BE PLACED ON PACKAGE. OUTSIDE OF THE PACKAGE HAS A RED   WHITE MARGIN FROM A HAZMAT SHIPPING PAPER. THERE IS ALSO AN INDENTATION ON THE BOX THE SAME SIZE AS A STANDARD HAZMAT SHIPPING PAPER. THE CONTENTS WERE ORIGINALLY THOUGHT TO BE A SEAT BELT PRETENSIONER BUT THE CORRECT DESCRIPTION IS AN AIR BAG FROM FORD. THE BACK OF THE DEVICE INDICATES IT IS FLAMMABLE. WE ALSO DISCOVERED THE ORIGINAL THERMAL LABEL. IT INDICATES IN ETT IT WAS SHIPPED ORIGINALLY FROM COUSELMAN AUTOMOTIVE RECYCLING TO MOHAMMED ALRAWE AND DECLARED AS A HAZMAT. THE ORIGINAL SHIPMENT WAS 08/08/2017 AND DELIVERED TO MR. MOHAMMED ALRAWE ON 8-14-17. THIS TIME, HOWEVER, NO HAZMAT INFO ON THE PACKAGE.

column168: WHILE OFFLOADING A VAN TRAILER FOR THE PURPOSE OF SEGREGATION AND CONSOLIDATION OF WASTE INTO OUTBOUND LOADS, A FACILITY TECHNICIAN NOTICED A DRUM CONTAINING PCB WASTE HAD A SMALL RELEASE FROM THE DRUM CLOSURE TO THE TRAILER FLOOR. NO GROUND, SOIL, OR WATER SOURCES OR DRAINS WERE IMPACTED. THE TECHNICIAN ALERTED FACILITY AND COMPANY MANAGEMENT, AND THE AREA WAS CORDONED OFF. A FIELD SERVICE EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM WAS SUMMONED. WEARING THE APPROPRIATE PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT, THIS TEAM DISCOVERED THAT THE DRUM CLOSURE HAD NOT BEEN PROPERLY CLOSED TO MANUFACTURER’S SPECIFICATION, AND OVER PACKED THE DRUM USING AN APPROPRIATE SPECIFICATION SALVAGE DRUM. THE CREW ALSO FULLY EMPTIED THE TRAILER, CLEANED THE TRAILER FLOOR, AND WITH GUIDANCE FROM OUR HEALTH AND SAFETY MANAGEMENT, APPLIED A SPECIAL PCB SEALING PAINT TO THE TRAILER FLOOR TO PREVENT FUTURE CONTAMINATION FROM THE IMPACTED WOOD. THE WASTE GENERATED FROM THE CLEANUP WAS PLACED INTO THE SALVAGE DRUM, AND THAT DRUM CONTAINED TO IT’S FINAL DESTINATION WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT. THIS RELEASE DID NOT MEET THE STATE REPORTING REQUIREMENTS FOR OHIO.
column169: THE ENTIRE BRANCH FROM WHICH THIS IMPROPERLY CLOSED DRUM ORIGINATED WAS PLACED ON A SAFETY STAND DOWN, AND GIVEN FULL RETRAINING ON PROPER DRUM CLOSURE AND CONTAINER INSPECTION AND LOAD SECUREMENT. THE DRIVER WHO DELIVERED THIS LOAD WAS ALSO GIVEN RETRAINING ON PROPER DRUM CLOSURE AND CONTAINER INSPECTION AND LOAD SECURMENT. AS A RELATED CORRECTIVE MEASURE, THE COMPANY HAS ALSO INSTITUTED A NEW LOAD SECUREMENT VERIFICATION PROTOCOL, WHICH INCLUDES A SECTION ON CONTAINER CLOSURE AND INSPECTION.

column168: Event # 66259..    No package failure.  Human error.      The driver arrived at consignee to unload. He connected the hose to the consignee's tank and started up the pump. He states that after a minute or so he noticed a slow drip from the connection. He shut down the pump but forgot to close the internal valve. When he disconnected the hose about 1 gallon of product shot out. He states the rest spilled onto the floor in the containment area. The consignee employee came over and hosed the released product down the drain of their containment area.

column168: On 9/13/17 received notification from Hub personnel at the BNSF Los Angeles IMF that FRA Hazardous Material Inspector  Steven Wolfe was inspecting Hazardous Material shipments at the BNSF Los Angeles IMF. Bulk tank container SNEU 600244 was inspected and noted a clear gel like substance dripping from the main bottom discharge valve, hardening at the base of the unit, spilling approximately 5 ounces. The end cap of the valve was missing the end cap from the valve, the top man way area was contaminated with residue from a previous loading unloading.  In the interest of safety, this unit was placed on hold from being loaded onto a railcar and then moved to a containment pit area pending inspection of  the tank. This unit was billed as an empty, however the unit had class 8 placarding (Corrosive) displayed on all four sides, with a description reading   DIDECYLDIMETHYLAMMONIUM CHLORIDE DISINFECTANTS, LIQUID. Approved Hazmat contractor United Pumping Services was called out to test the spilled product for Hazmat properties and to confirm if the unit contained product  residue. The spilled product tested positive for acidic hazardous properties, responder was able to confirm that this unit appeared to contain residue inside from a previous shipment, matching the properties from the spilled product. All contaminated areas associated with the leak were remediated by United Pumping Services and applied a new end cap on the main discharge valve.
column169: Per the BNSF Intermodal Rules and Policies Guide, empty portable tank container that previously contained hazardous commodities or has hazardous  residue must be billed with the appropriate STCC code. Schneider National  Bulk Intermodal will be required to provide new billing for the residue  inside of the unit. The unit will remain on hold at the BNSF Los Angeles IMF pending your instructions and updated billing.

column168: JBHU 277752 was noted as having an odor emitting from the container.  The container was moved to the Haz-pit where a contractor investigated. The load was 96 drums of isopropanol and air monitoring revealed high levels of flammable vapors. after letting the container air out for some time, the container was manually unloaded to prevent any contact with an ignition source. A single drum in the front of the container was noted as having two nail-sized punctures in the sidewall from an unknown source. No actual liquid was found as the liquid evaporated upon exit from the container. An estimated 40-gallons was lost judged off the level of the puncture location.
column169: Shipper must ensure that the load is properly handled to prevent punctures and future releases of hazardous materials into the environment.

column168: PRELOADER WAS UNLOADING A FEEDER AND SAW A WET PACKAGE. HE DID NOT TOUCH THE PKG AND NOTIFIED HIS SUPERVISOR. NOTIFIED THE DESIGNATED RESPONDER AND RMP. DESIGNATED RESPONDER OPENED THE BOX AND IDENTIFIED THE CONTENTS AS HAZARDOUS. RMP PERSON CALLED THE HAZMAT HELP DESK FOR CONFIRMATION OF AN UNDECLARED HAZMAT. THE BOX HAS NO HAZARDOUS OR ORMD MARKINGS BUT CONTAINS AN AUTO BATTERY CONTAINING SULFURIC ACID. CONFIRMATION #506178 FROM THE HAZMAT HELPLINE. WAS INSTRUCTED TO SEND PICTURES OF THE BOX, LABEL, AND CONTENTS TO SEND TO ADG COMPLIANCE FOR REVIEW, AND ENTER THE DAMAGE IN ETT AS AN UNDECLARED HAZMAT. THE BOX AND CONTENTS ARE BEING HELD IN THE CENTER IN A DMP BAG FOR ADG INSPECTION.
column169: SHIPPER SHOULD HAVE LABELLED BOX AS HAZMAT OR ORMD. BATTERY SHOULD HAVE PROPER PACKING SO IT COULD NOT SPILL AND ORIENTATION ARROWS TO KEEP IT UPRIGHT. THE ZIPLOC BAG SHOULD HAVE BEEN SEALED TO PREVENT SPILLAGE IN THE BOX. THERE IS ONLY A SMALL AMOUNT OF AIRBAGS FOR PACKING SO THE CONTENTS WERE ABLE TO SHIFT.

column168: WHEN OFFLOADING A RIGID PLASTIC BIN CONTAINING CANS OF PAINT RELATED WASTE, THE FORKLIFT DRIVER MISJUDGED THE DEPTH OF THE FORKS UNDER THE BIN, AND DROPPED THE BIN TO THE GROUND. AS A RESULTS, SEVERAL OF THE PAINT CANS WERE DAMAGED, AND RELEASED 2 GALLONS ONTO CONCRETE CONTAINMENT. THE DRIVER NOTIFIED FACILITY PERSONNEL AND MANAGEMENT IMMEDIATELY. FACILITY PERSONNEL, WEARING THE CORRECT PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT, FULLY CLEANED THE AREA, AND REPACKAGED THE DAMAGED INDIVIDUAL PAINT CANS. THE WASTE CONTINUED TO IT'S FINAL PROCESSING WITHOUT INCIDENT, AND THE WASTE MATERIALS GENERATED FROM THE CLEANUP WERE PLACED IN THE APPROPRIATE WASTE STREAM FOR DISPOSAL. IT WAS LATER DETERMINED THAT THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR HAD BEEN RUSHING, AND COULD HAVE TAKEN EXTRA TIME TO MOVE SOME ITEMS AROUND AND POSITION THE FORKLIFT TO GET A BETTER PURCHASE ON THIS CONTAINER. REPORTED TO THE VT DEC TO JAMES DONALDSON, NO REPORT NUMBER GIVEN.
column169: THE DRIVER OF THE FORKLIFT WAS GIVEN FORKLIFT OPERATION RETRAINING WAS RECERTIFIED ON SAFE FORKLIFT OPERATION. THE FORKLIFT DRIVER WAS ALSO GIVEN ADDITIONAL COUNSELING ON THE NEED TO NOT RUSH WHEN PERFORMING SAFETY SENSITIVE TASKS, AND THE NEED TO TAKE TIME TO BETTER PLAN ALL WORK SO AS TO MINIMIZE THE OPPORTUNITY FOR ACCIDENTS AND RELEASES.

column168: LOADERS WERE LOADING BOXES. WHILE LIFTING BOX INTO WALL CONTENTS MOVED AND CAUSED THE VALVE INSIDE THE BOX TO MOVE AND LOADERS HEARD LEAKING GAS SOUND. THEY STOPPED, GOT OUT OF TRAILER AND CAME TO FIND SUPERVISOR. WE STOPPED THE SORT AND I TOOK BOX OUTSIDE IMMEDIATELY. I SAW IT WAS MEDICAL EQUIPMENT ON SIDE OF BOX SO I OPENED BOX AND SEEN 5 COMPRESSED OXYGEN BOXES AND ONE THAT WAS LEAKING OXYGEN AT A HIGH STEADY STREAM. THE BOX WAS LABELED THAT IT WAS SUPPOSED TO BE EMPTIED PRIOR TO SHIPPING BUT THAT WAS NOT COMPLETED. IT TOOK ABOUT 20 MINS FOR CANISTER TO COMPLETELY DRAIN AT FULL OPENING. I THEN TOOK BOX BACK INSIDE AND THE OTHER HUB SUPERVISOR CALLED THE HAZMAT DESK TO SEE IF THIS WAS GOING TO BE CONSIDERED AN UNDECLARED HAZMAT. AFTER EMAILS AND PICTURES SUBMITTED THEY SAID TO SUBMIT.

column168: At 0645, when the Brewster Car Inspector was inspecting the inbound train, he noticed car GLNX 354 leaking from the protective housing.  He called the Brewster Yardmaster who then called myself, John Vergis Environmental Officer for WLE.  I came out and investigated the leak and found that the Liquid Valve on the B end of the car was leaking.  The valve was leaking through the valve plug.  I tried to tighten the valve to see if the leak would stop and it would not.  I cycled the valve open and closed to see if ice was in the valve seat but I could still not get it to stop leaking.  The leak was quite strong.  I was able to tighten the loose valve plug and get the leak to stop.  I had the car set to the shop for further investigation.  The shipper of the car had Sunpro come out to look at it and they said they valve needed replaced.  On 10-9-2017, Sunpro came out and flared the vapors off the car and replaced the B end Liquid Valve.  Then they put Nitrogen to the car to bubble test it.  The car passed the bubble test and was released for transportation.  They installed a new seal on the protective housing of #1607012.    NARRI:  2(4+5)=18                                   Code:115-282

column168: At 1316 on 09/12/2017 ERTS received a call from  Estes to report a spill. It was reported at 0600 ET on 9/12/2017, terminal personnel was unloading trailer #520839 when they discovered (1) 330 Gal Poly Tote of UN3265 Corrosive Liquid Acidic had been damaged due to impact with other freight inside of the trailer resulting in the release of approximately 25 Gallons of material to the dock floor. E3 Response was the contractor dispatched to clean up the release. Contractor transferred the remaining material into a new tote, placed neutralizer on the trailer floor, and containerized waste into drums. All waste transported off-site for disposal.

column168: A Clean Harbors Environmental Services Inc. van trailer containing hazardous waste arrived at the Bristol, CT transfer facility for an offload in order to transfer and consolidate its waste onto a van trailer for transportation to its intended waste disposal facility. Facility personnel noticed that there was a leaking 55-gallon drum on the truck. A response crew was notified, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment, entered the truck and assessed the situation. The leaking drum was found to have been properly closed and tightened but had a drum ring gasket had a significant cut in it, which led to the release.  The drum was resealed with a new gasket and then overpacked into properly rated salvage drum for continued transportation to the final disposal facility. The van trailer floor was cleaned with a cleaning compound and returned to service. The CT DEEP was notified spill #2017-04701.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of leaking was observed. This release was the direct result of a damaged gasket. The shipper was notified and advised to retrain its employees on proper container inspection and closure, with an emphasis on the inspection of component integrity prior to loading.

column168: DRIVERS WERE IN PROCESS OF UNLOADING CARGO TANK AT CUSTOMER LOCATION. A LEAK WAS NOTICED ON THE TOP OF 1 INCH VALVE IN UNLOADING TEE. RELEASE AMOUNT WAS DE MINIMIS, ESTIMATED AT LESS THAN 0.5 LITER. THE UNLOADING PROCESS WAS IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN. THE LEAK WAS OBSERVED AT THE 1 INCH FLANGE AND PLUG. AFTER SHUTDOWN, THE DRIVERS RESEATED THE GASKET, TIGHTENED THE BOLTS AND VENT PLUG. THE OFFLOADING WAS SUSPENDED, UNLOADING HOSE WAS CLEARED, AND THE DRIVERS RETURNED TO THE PLANT FOR INVESTIGATION.
column169: THE VALVE FROM THE CARGO TANK WAS SUBMITTED TO A 3RD PARTY FOR FAILURE ANALYSIS. THE VALVE PASSED THE REQUIRED TEST. THE MATERIAL OF CONSTRUCTION FOR THE FLANGE CONNECTING THE 1 INCH VALVE AND PLUG FOR POSSIBLE “GALLING” WAS ALSO ACCEPTABLE. THE PRE-TRIP CHECKLIST WAS COMPLETED AND INCLUDED A STEP TO VERIFY THE VALVE POSITION, AND THEADED PLUGS WERE TOOL TIGHT. OPERATIONS WILL RE-EMPHASIZE CURRENT PROCESS WITH ALL DRIVERS.

column168: September 27 2017, approximate at 5:30 PM in the Tecno Gas LPG filling facility, located in PR-891 Km. 14.8 Bo Pueblo, Corozal,P.R.  , During the LPG storage tanks filling processing, The   Empresas de Gas Bobtail operator Luis Hernandez open a valve located in the LPG system .The result was a LPG liquid release to the filling area, provoking a fire.  Tecno Gas Employee Albert Pagan was burned in 100% , Tecno Gas employee Edwin Cabrera was burned in the face and Tecno Gas Brian Cabrera was partially burned in one elbow.Empresas de Gas Bobtail operator Luis Hernandez was burned 90% . All injured persons were mobilized to the hospital.  Fire department, police and Emergency Management Agency team participate in the emergency work.  I in person participated in the extinction operation. After the fire was extinguished, we extracted all the LPG from the tank that was on fire using an extraction pump.    Two weeks after the incident Albert Pagan and Luis Hernandez was disconnected to the life-support equipment in the Hospital and die.      At this time the incident is still under investigation.
column169: Because the incident is still under investigation the Tecnogas operation in Corozal was close.  Empresas de Gas Bobtail operation still in function. Several safety meeting has been done with the operators.

column168: 48 X 55 GALLON STEEL DRUMS SHIPPED TO CWM AS NON-REGULATED MATERIAL (ZN/SI/AI OVERSPRAY). MATERIAL WAS EXPECTED TO BE DRY USED PRODUCT, SUITABLE FOR LANDFILL DISPOSAL. UPON DELIVERY, IT WAS NOTED THAT LIQUID HAD SPILLED OUT OF SOME OF THE DRUMS DUE TO LOOSE RINGS ON THE DRUMS. SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED IN THE BOX VAN AND WAS CLEANED UP BY CWM. UPON INSPECTION OF THE DRUM CONTENTS, IT WAS NOTED THAT 4 DRUMS CONTAINED DRY GRAY POWDER, OTHERS DARK GRAY GRITTY SOLIDS AND NUMEROUS DRUMS CONTAINED WATER ON TOP OF DARK GRAY GRITTY SOLIDS. CWM QUESTIONED THE DISCREPANCY OF THE PHYSICAL APPEARANCE AND THE PRESENCE OF FREE LIQUID (WATER).THE GENERATOR INDICATED THAT THE GRAY POWDER WAS OVERSPRAY CONTAINING 5% ALUMINUM POWDER/95% ZINC POWDER THAT HAD BEEN SWEPT UP FROM THE FLOOR. THE SDS PROVIDED FOR THE ALUMINUM POWDER INDICATED THAT THE MATERIAL IS A DOT CLASS 4.3, DANGEROUS WHEN WET. THE HMT ALSO CLASSIFIES ZINC POWDER AS CLASS 4.3.THE GENERATOR EXPLAINED THAT THE DARK GRITTY SOLIDS WERE THE OVERSPRAY MATERIAL CAPTURED BY THE WATERFALL DUST COLLECTION SYSTEM. CWM CHECKED A NUMBER OF THE DRUMS WITH AND WITHOUT FREE LIQUID AND FOUND POSITIVE READINGS WITH A COMBUSTIBLE GAS METER..CWM CONSERVATIVELY ADDED CLASS 4.3 LABELS TO ALL 48 DRUMS AND REJECTED THEM BACK TO THE GENERATOR FOR ASSESSMENT AND RESOLUTION. A COPY OF THE INBOUND AND OUTBOUND SHIPPING PAPERS IS ATTACHED.

column168: THIS UNLABELED AND UNMARKED BOX WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING DURING THE SORTING OPERATION AND WAS OPENED AND HELD FOR INSPECTION. ONE OF THE TWO INNER METAL CAN SLID'S HAD COME LOOSE CAUSING THE PAINT TO SPILL. MY STATION COULD NOT CONTACT MY OFFICE DUE TO SOME PHONE ISSUES AT MY LOCATION, (AS WE HAD RECENTLY CHANGED PHONE NUMBERS). I SPOKE TO THE SHIPPER AND ASKED IF HE COULD PROVIDE A SDS SHEET REGARDING THIS PRODUCT, AND THEY DID. THE SHIPMENT WAS REGULATED AND THEY FAILED TO MOVE IT BY FEDEX GROUND, AND SHIPPED IT BY EXPRESS. I NOTIFIED SHANE ALLEN '(BY EMAIL & VOICEMAIL) AT THE SEA / FAA OFFICE TO ADVISE OF THE INCIDENT AT 16:50 ON 9-26-2017. I LATER LEARNED FROM MY PEOPLE AT GTFR THAT THEY HAD THROWN AWAY THE OUTER PACKAGE AS IT WAS ALL WET AND MESSED UP, AND THEY DID NOT KNOW THEY SHOULD HAVE HELD ON TO IT. I CALLED SHANE ALLEN THIS AM TO SPEAK DIRECTLY WITH HIM IN REVIEW. ONCE THE FAA IS FINISHED, WE CAN RELEASE THE SHIPMENT TO THE SHIPPER WHO WILL DRIVE DOWN TO PICK IT. I PROVIDED A NOTIFICATION OF THE INCIDENT, THE SDS, & FOUR PHOTOS OF THE INNER CANS TO SHANE ALLEN.

column168: Event # 66255.    Driver arrived at Shipper to load.  Shipper was approx 1/2 through the loading process when a slow drip was discovered from belly of trailer.      Product was offloaded and trailer was placed in shop.       Inspection found that the bottom sump flange bolts were loose. Either were not tightened at last shop that worked on it, or they loosened in transit.
column169: Sump Flange bolts were tightened which corrected issue.

column162: SVP, TRANSPORTATION COMPLIANCE AND HEALTH & SAFETY
column168: A vehicle operated by Safety Kleen Systems, Inc was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a 10 day transfer facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities on a single transport vehicle for continued transportation. During the unloading operation  the pallet of drums was placed on uneven concrete floor.  As the forklift operator approached the pallet, readied his forks through the pallet, the pallet broke causing the forks to strike the drum.  The operator immediately stopped work and placed the drum on its side, added absorbent pads and halted the leak.    Facility personnel assembled a response team who proceeded to place the compromised  container into a suitable salvage drum. In addition, all clean-up debris and materials used to decontaminate the floor were collected and placed into the salvage drum. Once complete, the container was secured and was placed onto the trailer for continued transportation.  The forklift operator was pulled from forklift operations pending investigation and retraining.
column169: Since the root cause of the incident was determined to be unsafe forklift operation, a review of the incident and the unsafe practices was immediately reviewed with SKS  shipping and receiving technician(s).   Forklift operator will be formally retrained in loading and unloading, pallet integrity, as well as forklift operations.   Additionally all drivers, dock personnel, warehouse personnel, and material handlers will ensure pallets are checked as thoroughly as they check the containers so as to ensure integrity of the pallet and its support of the containers resting on them.  One other note: this spill happened on 8/03/2017 and was not reported to me until 09/20/2017.  Retraining to all personnel, including management team on the company's requirement to immediately notify the company of spills, releases, and/or reactions.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: While unloading a trailer containing hazardous material for consolidation into an outbound load, facility personnel noticed that a cubic yard box had developed a leak onto the trailer floor. The release also made its way through trailer floor, and onto the paved trailer storage area. No soil, water ways, or sewers were impacted. Facility personnel immediately deployed boom and absorbent to prevent the spread of the release.  A response crew was notified, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment, entered the truck, unloaded the leaking cubic yard box, and opened the box to investigate. The box inner liner was found to have been punctured, likely during loading; the box did not contain sufficient absorbents to contain a spill if there was an issue with one of the inner paint cans.  The response crew checked the integrity and closures of the inner containers and repacked the contents into a new cubic yard box of appropriate specification for the material; sufficient absorbent was added to the box to prevent another accidental release. The trailer floor was cleaned with a cleaning compound and returned to service. The pavement impacted was also cleaned with cleaning compound.     This release did not meet the reporting criteria for the State of Ohio
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of leaking or breakage was observed. All employees at the branch which loaded this cubic yard box were given retraining on inner package closure inspection, and the need to use the correct type and amount of absorbents when packing this type of box with inner containers of liquid paint related materials.

column168: WHEN PRELOADING A SMALL AMOUNT OF HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTION TO THE TANK TO PRETREAT AN ANTICIPATED SEWAGE PUMP OUT. THE FACILITY TECHNICIAN NOTICED THE REAR DOOR SEAL LEAKING. THE VEHICLE WAS IN CONTAINMENT; ONLY A VERY SMALL AMOUNT IMPACTED THE CONTAINMENT CONCRETE, MOST BEING CAPTURED BY THE VEHICLE'S DRIP PAN AND ABSORBENT PADS. NO WATER OR SOIL WAS IMPACTED. THE FACILITY TECHNICIAN CEASED LOADING, AND IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED MANAGEMENT, WHO MADE THE NECESSARY NOTIFICATION TO TRANSPORTATION COMPLIANCE, ENVIRONMENTAL COMPLIANCE, AND HEALTH AND SAFETY. A FACILITY CREW, WEARING THE APPROPRIATE PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT, WAS CALLED IN TO CLEAN UP THE SMALL AMOUNT OF RELEASED LIQUID, REMOVED ANY OF THE LIQUID LOADED INTO THIS UNIT, AND RINSE THIS UNIT OUT SO IT COULD BE TAKEN TO BE SERVICED. ALL WASTE GENERATED FROM THE CLEAN UP FROM THIS RELEASE WAS PLACED INTO THE APPROPRIATE WASTE STREAM FROM LATER DISPOSAL.
column169: THIS WAS A RENTAL VEHICLE THAT HAD BEEN SUBJECT TO PREVIOUS WEAR AND TEAR. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE REAR DOOR SEAL WAS DETERIORATED, AND THAT THE REAR DOOR CLAMPING BOLTS WERE IN NEED OF REPLACEMENT. THE VEHICLE REPAIRS WERE COMPLETED, AND IT HAS BEEN USED SINCE WITHOUT INCIDENT. THE DRIVER INVOLVED WITH THIS INCIDENT WAS ALSO GIVEN RETRAINING ON PROPER VEHICLE PRE-TRIP INSPECTIONS, WITH AN EMPHASIS ON TANK CLOSURE AND DOOR SEAL INSPECTIONS.

column42: AMMONIUM NITRATE, WITH NOT MORE THAN 0.2%  OF COMBUSTIBLE MATERIALS, INCLUDING ANY ORGANIC SUBSTANCE CALCULATED AS CARBON TO THE EXCLUSION OF ANY OTHER ADDED SUBSTANCE
column168: AT 6:20 AM ON 9/26/17 AUSTIN POWDER CO, TRUCK WAS TRAVELING WEST ON HIGHWAY 228 IN A RURAL PORTION OF MEADE COUNTRY KY. THE SUM WAS NOT YET UP AND A SENSE FOG WAS PRESENT. THE DRIVER, WHO WAS FAMILIAR WITH THIS STRETCH OF ROAD, WAS EN ROUTE TO A CUSTOMER IN THE AREA. HE WAS LOADED WITH 45000 POUNDS OF AMMONIUM NITRATE (UN1942). THE ROAD IS A 2 LANE PAVED ROAD WITH NARROW BERNS THAT GIVE WAY TO A STEEP DOWNWARD SLOPE. THE SPEED LIMIT IS 55 BUT  DUE TO CONDITIONS, THE DRIVER SPEED WAS BETWEEN 25 AND 45 IN THE MOMENTS BEFORE THE ACCIDENT. THE TRAILER TANDEMS AND THEN THE TRACTOR LEFT THE ROADWAY. THE DRIVER HEAVILY APPLIED THE BRAKE AND ATTEMPTED TO STEER THE VEHICLE BACK ONTO THE ROAD. HE SUCCEEDED IN GETTING THE TRUCK BACK ON THE ROAD, BUT THE TRAILER REMAINDER OFF AS HE ROLLED NEARLY TO A STOP. DUE TO THE ANGLE OF THE TRAILER, THE COMBINATION OVERTURNED ONTO THE PASSENGER SIDE AND CAME TO REST IN A ROCKY AREA WITH HEAVY VEGETATION ON THE NORTH SIDE EMBANKMENT. THE DRIVER RECEIVED MINOR INJURIES, BUT WAS ABLE TO CONTACT 911. WHO IN TURN NOTIFIED AUSTIN POWDER AGENCY. FIRST RESPONDERS AND WRECKERS WERE DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE. A SPILL RESPONSE CREW WAS DISPATCHED FOR LOUISVILLE. AUSTIN PERSONNEL ALSO GOT TO THE SCENE QUICKLY. THE TRUCK AND TRAILER WERE PUT UPRIGHT AND A SMALL HOLE THE SIZE OF A SLIVER DOLLAR WAS FOUND ON THE PASSENGER SIDE OF THE TANKER ABOUT MIDWAY DOWN. THE 100 POUNDS OF MATERIAL THAT HAD LEAKED WERE PLACED IN A BARREL AND TAKEN 10 REMAINING MILES TO THE CUSTOMERS SITE, WHERE IT WAS USED FOR BLASTING. THE TANKER WAS TOWED THERE AND THE REMAINDER OF THE LOAD WAS USED FOR THE SAME.
column169: SERVICING THIS CUSTOMER REQUIRES TRAVELING ON BATTELTOWN ROAD. THEY ARE ALLOWING US TO BEGIN MAKING DELIVERIES AT LATER IN THE DAY AS THE DRIVER INDICATE THAT THE DOG AND DARKNESS WERE CONTRIBUTING FACTORS TO THIS ACCIDENT. ANN EMPLOYEE (DRIVING A NON-CMV) ALWAYS PRECEDES THESE BULK VEHICLES TO THIS CUSTOMER. IT HAS BEEN DECIDED THAT THEY WILL NOTIFY THE DRIVERS OF THE BULK VEHICLES OF WEATHER CONDITIONS INCLUDING FOG UPON THEIR ARRIVAL. THIS WILL ALLOW US TO RESCHEDULE OR CANCEL DELIVERIES IF NEEDED. FINALLY, THERE IS AN AREA JUST AFTER TURNING ONTO BATTLETOWN ROAD WHERE A DRIVER CAN SAFETY PULL OFF AND SIT. WE ARE ADVISING OUR DRIVER GROUP THAT THEY SHOULD UTILIZE THIS ARA AS NEEDED. WAITING THERE WAS LONG AS NEEDED UNTIL FOG CONDITION IMPROVE.

column168: On September 12, 2017 At 1450 ET, ERTS received a call from Landstar Ranger to report a spill located at the Zuniga Logistics terminal in Laredo, TX. It was reported at 1440 ET, driver Mustapha of truck #421157 / trailer #721157 was off loading at Zuqiga Logistics located at 12013 Sara Road in Laredo, TX when terminal personnel discovered (1) tote of UN1993 Flammable Liquid damaged due to unknown causes releasing approximately 3 Gallons of material to the trailer floor. ERTS dispatched E3 Environmental for the response. Once the contractor arrived on site, E3 determined the cause of the spill was impact with adjacent freight resulting in the 3 gallon spill.     Approximately 270 Gallons was transferred into a new tote and sent on to the customer. The 3 Gallons of material had been impacted with granular absorbents and containerized into waste containers. Waste was taken off site and disposed of by E3 Environmental.

An ISO Container rolled over while being moved around the terminal yard causing product to be released.  The site of the release was cordoned off and a Hazmat response team was mobilized to the scene.  The team identified that the source of the release was a loose manway cover.  Once the manway cover was tightened, the release stopped.  The duration of the release was approximately three (3) hours.  The product solidified almost immediately upon release.  The Hazmat team cleaned the product from the ISO container and no further mitigation was needed.      Our Event #66244-1.

On 9/25/2017 at approximately 12:15 PT, DBUX 300264 arrived the Tidewater Refinery in Pasco, WA with obvious wetness around the tank shell in the area of the manway.  Tidewater personnel inspected the tank car and opened the manway and found a missing manway nozzle gasket.  Car was a load of diesel fuel.  It was offloaded, tank shell cleaned, and gasket replaced.  No apparent release to the environment.  Car was secured and released back into service.
column169: Shipper needs to ensure no missing, loose, or defective components or devices prior to offering into transportation per regulations.  Re-training and spot auditing for compliance as necessary.

column168: On 9/27/17 FRA inspector along with BNSF personnel found BNSF 880377 loaded with diesel fuel leaking droplets from the bottom outlet cap assembly.  BNSF Hazmat Responder found the bottom outlet cap not wrench tight.  The outlet valve was cycled to clear suspected debris and cap assembly was inspected for damaged gasket.  Gasket was found serviceable, and cap assembly was replaced to a wrench tight condition and observed for further leakage.  Leak was stopped and car was released for service.  Minimal impact to environment with droplets on railroad ties was wiped up as well as cap assembly.
column169: Review loading and pre-trip procedures to ensure car load is properly packaged for transportation to include tightness of all valves and fittings.  Re-train personnel, brief on incident, and spot check as needed.

column25: Schneider National Inc. by Ecolab Inc.
column168: BNSF S. Seattle Hub Operations notified BNSF Load and Ride Solutions of top unit SNLU 152301 that was discovered during deramping operations to have been leaking a red liquid onto the bottom unit and railcar it was riding on during transit from seepage through the floor. The unit was removed and placed on a chassis for inspection and remediation while the bottom unit was moved to the containment pit for cleaning. NRC Environmental was contacted to inspect and remediate the unit.    NRC Environmental inspected the unit and found cargo consisting of a mixed load of hazmat liquid (herbicide) in stretch wrapped drums on pallets and large liquid totes; the source of the leak was discover ed to be liquid herbicide sloshing from out of a loose pressure cap on a possibly overfilled tote. NRC removed all of the cargo from the doorway towards the leak source to clean the floor, remediated the leak, and reloaded the unit and secured with floor blocking. NRC also cleaned the outside of the bottom unit affected during transit. This unit is released for outgate.  Product was identified as TruPower 3 Selective Herbicide blended chemical transported as a Class 9 material placarded 3082.

column168: AFTER THE UNLOADING PROCESS WAS COMPLETED BY SOLVAY PERSONNEL OF A VEOLIA OWNED TRAILER THAT HAZMAT ENVIRONMENTAL GROUP. INC’S DRIVER DELIVERED, THE OPERATOR FAILED TO RELIEVE THE PRESSURE AND UNHOOKED THE PRODUCT VALVE BEFORE SHUTTING IT OFF, RESULTING IN APPROX. 25 GALS. OF MATERIAL BEING RELEASED ONTO THE GROUND, THEN FORMING A LARGE CLOUD INTO THE SURROUNDING AREA. THE UNLOADING PROCESS TOOK APPROX. 3 HOURS AND HAZMAT’S DRIVER WAS SITTING IN THE CAB OF TRACTOR DURING THIS TIME. HE WAS NEITHER OBSERVING NOR PARTICIPATING IN THE UNLOADING PROCESS. SOLVAY’S PROTOCOL DOES NOT ALLOW THE DRIVER OUT OF THE TRUCK. A RED CHAIN STATING “NO ENTRANCE” IS HUNG IN THE UNLOADING AREA.  THE SHELTER IN PLACE ALARM WAS ENGAGED AND THE UNLOADER ESCORTED OUR DRIVER INSIDE THE ADJACENT BUILDING, WHERE HE REMAINED SEQUESTERED FOR 5 HOURS. UPON THE ARRIVAL OF THE FIRE DEPT., THE VALVE WAS SHUT OFF AND WATER WAS SPRAYED ON THE CLOUD PER THE SOLVAY SITE MANAGER’S INSTRUCTION.  PROPER PPE WAS DONNED BY SOLVAY PERSONNEL AND NO INJURIES WERE REPORTED.  NOTE: INFORMATION PERTAINING TO THE “UNKNOWN” RESPONSES WAS NOT PROVIDED UPON REQUEST.
column169: CONSIGNEE WILL PROVIDE REFRESHER TRAINING TO ALL UNLOADER OPERATORS AND REVALIDATION OF TRAINING PRIOR TO THE NEXT DELIVERY OF CHLOROSULFONIC ACID TO THIS LOCATION.

column168: ON SEPTEMBER 3, 2017, SOLVAY RECEIVED A TANKER TRUCK OF ETHYL CHLORIDE FROM AXIALL. AT APPROXIMATELY 5:35 A.M., THE DRIVER/UNLOADED HAD COMPLETED THE TANKER HOOKUP UP AT THE SOLVAY ETHYL CHLORIDE UNLOADING STATION AND BEGAN TO UNLOAD THE CONTENTS OF HIS TANKER INTO THE ETHYL CHLORIDE STORAGE TANK. AFTER APPROXIMATELY 10 MINUTES HE NOTICED A WET AREA BEHIND THE TANKER TRUCK. SUSPECTING A POTENTIAL LEAK, THE UNLOADER IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE SOLVAY LOADER AND THE UNLOADING PROCESS WAS STOPPED AND THE UNLOADING VALVES ON THE TANKER WERE CLOSED. THE SOLVAY LOADER (LOADER) VERIFIED THAT MATERIAL WAS MISTING OUT OF THE TANKER FROM AROUND THE REAR MANWAY AREA.  THE SOLVAY EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM (ERT) WAS ACTIVATED TO RESPOND TO THE LEAK AND DETERMINED BEST PATH FORWARD TO CORRECT THE LEAK. THE SITE ERT DETERMINED THAT THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK WAS STAINLESS STEEL TUBING NEAR THE REAR MANWAY. SOLVAY CONFIRMED WITH AXIALL THAT THE TUBING WAS A PART OF THE TANKER’S VENT SYSTEM USED DURING THE LOADING OF THE MATERIAL. SOLVAY FOUND TWO 1/16” VALVES IN THE VENT MANIFOLD OPEN. ONE VALVE WAS A THREE WAY VALVE LEFT IN THE “VENT UP” POSITION AND THE OTHER WAS A VALVE LEFT SLIGHTLY OPEN WHICH ALLOWED THE UNLOADING HOSE TO VENT. IT WAS NOT OBVIOUS THAT THIS VALVE WAS CRACKED OPEN BECAUSE THE VALVE HANDLE WAS MISSING. ONCE THE VALVES WERE CLOSED, THE LEAK WAS STOPPED AND THE TANK TRUCK WAS UNLOADED AS SCHEDULED.
column169: SOLVAY IS TAKING ACTIONS TO MAKE SURE THE VENT MANIFOLD VALVES ARE CLOSED PRIOR TO UNLOADING AND HAS ASKED THAT AXIALL CONDUCT A ROOT CAUSE INVESTIGATION TO DETERMINE HOW THE TANK TRUCK WAS SHIPPED WITH THE VENT VALVES IN THE OPEN POSITION.   SOLVAY HAS REQUESTED THAT AXIALL COMPLETE A THOROUGH INVESTIGATION ON THEIR END AND SHARE THE ROOT CAUSE AND ACTIONS TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE. SOLVAY HAS SPECIFICALLY REQUESTED INFORMATION FROM AXIALL REGARDING AXIALL LOADER TRAINING RECORDS, CONTAINER INSPECTION REPORTS AND LOADING CHECKLISTS AS PERTINENT INFORMATION IN COMPLETING THE INVESTIGATION ON OUR END. ONCE THESE DOCUMENTS ARE MADE AVAILABLE, SOLVAY WILL BE ABLE TO COMPLETE A ROOT CAUSE ANALYSIS AND DEVELOP ACTIONS TO PREVENT RECURRENCE.

column168: One of ECRI inbound AMS cars, SHPX210956 was leaking from a bottom flange at Shire Oaks.  It only leaked when moved.  Not leaking while parked.   Eric Waddell and I responded to the call, and Advansix was able to identify SHPX210894 that was outbound from the plant tonight empty from the yardmaster’s list of cars moving.  Advansix will get the leaking car transloaded into SHPX210894.  So, there will need to be some paperwork addressed, as we will now be receiving the car that just left plant empty. Car was successfully transloaded into SHPX210894, SHPX210956 was moved to ACF tank car facility in Milton, PA under OTMA approval from FRA.
column169: SHPX 210 series cars have been Identified under FRA directive RWD No. 2016-01   Car has been cleaned and purged with placards removed. Car has been security sealed by FRA at the BOV, BOV caps, manway cover and top fittings protective housing as an anti-tamper measure.     Actions are as follows.  · Shipper of record - AdvanSix, Inc.   o Is to apply for an FRA OTMA-1 for subject car to move via NS Railroad from current location of Elrama, PA to the ACF tank car facility located in Milton, PA   § FRA will expedite OTMA application in an effort to move car to home shop ASAP.  · Railroad carrier – Norfolk Sothern Railroad   o Is to assess OTMA-1 and if approved, provide movement of subject tank car as detailed above.  · Tank car owner/Tank car facility – ARI/ARL/ACF   o Is to notify FRA (Randy Keltz) when car arrives at Milton facility – No action is to be taken once car arrives and car must remain sealed.  · FRA   o Will expedite and process OTMA-1 for authorized movement.   o FRA (Randy Keltz) will arrange with tank car owner/facility, shipper and railroad all joint inspection efforts (time and date).   o FRA will remove all DOT-FRA seals to facilitate joint inspection.     As information, a preliminary engineering review has been made by FRA and the OTMA-1 will be processed for movement of this car on its own running gear.    AdvanSix currently performs a visual inspection before release for transit per the FRA directive.    Manufacture (ARL) have communicated to AdvanSix that we should not have any other issues with this car Series.

column168: LOADED TRAILER DEPARTED THE SHIPPER AND IMMEDIATELY STOPPED AT AN INTERSECTION. WHEN PULLING FORWARD THE PRODUCT IN THE TRAILER ROLLED TO THE BACK OF THE TRAILER AND CAME OUT OF THE FILL LINE VALVE ON THE TOP OF THE TRAILER. THIS VALVE HAD NOT SHUT PROPERLY AND APPROXIMATELY 18 GALLONS SPILLED ON THE TRAILER AND STREET. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED TO THE STREET FOR A STRETCH OF ABOUT 200 FEET DUE TO THE TIME INVOLVED FOR THE DRIVER TO REALIZE THE LEAK AND STOP THE TRUCK/TRAILER. THE SHIPPER OF THIS PRODUCT AND THE LOCAL VOLUNTEER FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED IMMEDIATELY. THEY USED SODA ASH TO NEUTRALIZE AND ABSORB, AND CONTROLLED THE FLOW OF TRAFFIC AWAY FROM THE SPILLED PRODUCT. YOUNG ENVIRONMENTAL OUT OFF LINT, ML WAS CALLED IN TO COMPLETE THE CLEAN-UP AND DISPOSE OF THE CONTAMINATED SODA ASH. THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT FINISHED THE CLEAN-UP BY FLOODING THE AREA WITH WATER. THE TOTAL DURATION OF THE CLEAN-UP WAS ABOUT 12 HOURS.
column169: THE VALVE THAT FAILED WAS MANUALLY CLOSED AND SECURED AT THE SCENE TO ELIMINATE THE RISK OF ADDITIONAL PRODUCT SPILLING. AFTER THE TRAILER WAS UNLOADED AND WASHED, THE VALVE WAS REPLACED BY OUR QUEST LINER SHOP IN BLUE GRASS, IOWA. IT HAS BEEN COMMUNICATED TO THE DRIVERS THAT HANDLE THIS PARTICULAR TRAILER TO DOUBLE CHECK ALL VALVES TO VERIFY THEY CLOSED PROPERLY BEFORE DEPARTING THE LOADING RACK. WE WORKED WITH THE SHIPPER OF THE PRODUCT TO DEVELOP A CHECK LIST FOR THE LOADER AND DRIVER TO COMPLETE BEFORE THE TRAILER DEPARTS THE PLANT. DISCREPANCIES WILL BE CORRECTED BEFORE THE DRIVER IS ALLOWED TO LEAVE THE LOADING FACILITY.

column168: During the unloading of rack truck for the purposes of consolidation and shipment of waste to a final destination, facility personnel discovered that an IBC container was leaking from its cap; this release of 6 oz. was isolated to just the top of the INC, and the release did not impact any ground, soil, or any water sources,    Appropriately trained facility personnel donned the correct personal protective equipment and removed the IBC tote cap to inspect it. Finding there to be no issues with the cap, it was screwed back, properly tightened to the manufacturer's specification. The cause of the release was determined to be the an improperly tightened fill cap.     he released liquid was cleaned up and the surface of the IBC neutralized. The waste generated by the cleanup was placed into an appropriate branch waste stream for later disposal. The IBC then continued to its final destination without incident.      This release was reported tot the State of Connecticut DEEP, report #2017-05009.T
column169: The driver responsible for transporting this IBC was given additional container closure and inspection training, with an emphasis on the requirement to check all IBC closures before transporting. This driver will also receive a documented written warning when he returns from a leave of absence.

column168: ON 9/28/2017 AN SAFETY-KLEEN DRIVER PICKED UP 4 DRUMS OF WASTE PETROLEUM DISTILLATES NOS, MANIFEST #006194486SKS FROM A CUSTOMER SITE.  AS HE WAS SERVICING ANOTHER CUSTOMER HE NOTICE 1 OF THE 4 DRUMS HE PICKED UP EARLIER WAS BULGING FROM BOTH THE TOP AND BOTTOM OF THE DRUM. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY OVER-PACKED THE DRUM AND RETURNED TO HIS BRANCH LOCATION. ON 9/29/2017 A STRONG ODOR LIKE PROPANE WAS COMING FROM THE OVER-PACK. EMPLOYEES REMOVED THE OVER-PACK FROM THE WAREHOUSE AND PLACED IT OUTSIDE IN AN ISOLATED AREA. THE BUNG CAP WAS REMOVED FROM THE LID ON THE OVER-PACK AND NOTICE THE DRUM INSIDE WAS OFF-GASSING . A 3RD PARTY RESPONSE TEAM WAS BROUGHT IN CONDUCT AIR MONITORING AND FOUND READINGS OF CO AND VOC’S- VOLITALE ORGANIC COMPOUNDS. IT WAS DETERMINED TO KEEP THE DRUM ISOLATED AND ALLOW IT OFF-GAS. THE FOLLOWING WEEK CONDUCTED MORE AIR MONITORING AND IT WAS DETERMINE THERE WAS NO ISSUE WITH THE DRUM AND IT WAS SHIPPED FOR DISPOSAL TO THE INTENDED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY. AN INVESTIGATION FOUND THAT THE CUSTOMER INTRODUCED SOME OFF-SPEC HYDROCARBONS INTO THE DRUM AND FROM THE POSSIBILITY OF AGITATION DURING TRANSIT CAUSE THE DRUM TO BULGE.
column169: THE CUSTOMER IS LOOKING INTO HOW THE OFF-SPEC MATERIAL WAS PLACED IN THE DRUM AND WILL MAKE CHANGES SO IT WILL NOT HAPPEN AGAIN.

column168: WE AS THE FREIGHT FORWARDER (TLR) WERE REVIEWING EXPORT DOCUMENTS AND DISCOVERED A DISCREPANCY ON SHIPPER’S INVOICE. SHIPPER WAS NOT ONLY SUPPOSED TO BE SENDING NON-HAZ INERT BULLET CORES. WE NOTICED BRASS CASES, ALSO USUALLY NON-HAZ. WE ASKED THE SHIPPER ABOUT THE BRASS AND SHIPPER ADVISED THAT THE BOXES CONTAINED EMPTY CASES WITH PRIMER. WE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED LOCAL FAA INSPECTOR OF HAZMAT CARGO THAT WAS NOT DECLARED. THIS SHIPMENT WAS INTENDED TO BE AN AIR EXPORT SHIPMENT. SHIPPER ARRANGED THEIR OWN TRANSPORT TO OUR WAREHOUSE AND OUR WAREHOUSE HAD NO KNOWLEDGE OF THE HAZMAT BECAUSE THE BOXES WERE NOT MARKED. WE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE WAREHOUSE BUT THEY HAD ALREADY MOVED CARGO TO THEIR HAZMAT AREA BECAUSE THEY ASSUMED IT WAS HAZ DUE TO THE COMPANY NAME BARNES BULLETS WAS ON THE OUTER PACKS.
column169: THIS SHIPPER BARNES BULLETS DOES NOT NORMALLY SHIP HAZ AND THIS WAS AN HONEST MISTAKE BY THEM HOWEVER THEIR PARENT COMPANY REMINGTON IS STILL UNCLEAR AS TO WHY THERE IS A VIOLATION EVEN THOUGH WE HAVE TRIED TO EXPLAIN IT. I WOULD RECOMMEND THAT THE RESPONSIBLE PARTIES AT REMINGTON ARMS CO. TAKE A CURRENT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TRAINING COURSE.

column72: Brenner Tank LLC dba Beall Trailers
column168: APP Driver was making a delivery to an AST at a customer site on 9/13/17 around 12:40 pm. As he was positioned squarely filling the diesel fill on the split gas/diesel AST, he brought the nozzle out slightly to view the tank level. Just as he did this, his left foot lost grip on the stairway he was standing on to access the tank fills and he slid back, falling against the railing. The motion caused the nozzle to come out of the tank and spray out. Since it was on a swivel, it spun around, spraying diesel on both sides of the tank. This tank is located on a concrete dock adjacent to Lake Union, and about 2 oz of the spill also splashed into the Lake. The driver quickly shut off the flow and deployed clean-up materials for the free product. Most had dropped to the concrete and asphalt in a "splash" fashion and the height from which is splashed from caused the spill to appear larger than it was. It was estimated that the total spill was less than 10 gallons, with the before mentioned 2 oz reaching the lake. Taryn Olson went to the scene and made appropriate notifications for the Department of Ecology and dispatched NRC Environmental for clean-up. Ecology reps onscene viewed the spill and lake and made the determination of the 2 oz spill to the lake, as no visible sheen remained present. NRC cleaned up the affected asphalt and concrete, being careful not to allow any of the wash water to drip into the lake. While Taryn was onscene, driver re-created the position he had been in and how the spill had occurred. Through investigation with him, it was determined that the root caused was that the tread on his safety boot was worn, which caused him to lose the grip in his stance and fall backward, spilling the product. Driver stated he would be purchasing new boots right away. This spill was NOT the result of any packaging or equipment failure.
column169: Better PPE program for boots, additional training for filling when standing on platforms/stairways like this.

column168: ON FRIDAY SEPTEMBER 28TH 2017 AT 3:45PM UNIVAR DRIVER ARRIVED AT CITY OF NAPA JAMIESON WTP TO MAKE A SODIUM HYDROXIDE (CAUSTIC) 25% DELIVERY. THE DRIVER COMPLETED HIS DELIVERY AND LEFT THE SITE WITHOUT INCIDENT. THE FOLLOWING DAY SEPTEMBER 29TH I WAS NOTIFIED BY OUR UNIVAR MUNICIPAL SPECIALIST THAT OUR DRIVER HAD SPILLED DRIPS OF CAUSTIC THE PRIOR DAY AT THE CUSTOMER SITE. I CONTACTED THE CUSTOMER AT THE WATER PLANT AND SPOKE WITH THE PLANT AND SPOKE WITH MY ON-SITE BOS TO HELP INVESTIGATE THE INCIDENT. I THEN CONTACTED MY DISTRICT MANAGER (DM), REGULATORY MANAGER (RM) AND SAFETY MANAGER (SM) TO INFORM THEM OF THE INCIDENT. OVER THE NEXT SEVERAL HOURS I WAS IN CONTACT WITH A UNIVAR-CONTRACTED ENVIRONMENTAL VENDOR, THE CUSTOMER, UNIVAR BOS, FIRE DEPARTMENT, AND CHP. THE DRIPS WERE TRACED TO THE CUSTOMER DRIVEWAY, KIRKLAND RANCH RD, NB SR-29, EB/WB LANES OF SR 12 THE HIGHWAY (ABOUT 1.5-2 MILES). UNIVAR-CONTRACTED VENDOR ARRIVED AT THE SCENE AT APPROXIMATELY 4:30PM TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL ON THE CUSTOMER PROPERTY. CAL TRANS AND THE LOCAL COUNTY ROAD SERVICE PARTNERED TO CLEAN UP THE REMAINDER OF THE SPILL ALONG THE HIGHWAY AND LOCAL COUNTY ROAD.
column169: TO PREVENT RECURRENCE OF THE RELEASE, ADDITIONAL TRAINING CAN BE CONDUCTED FOR CORROSIVE MATERIAL DRIVERS TO REDUCE INCIDENTS AND STOP ISSUES IN TRANSIT. TRANSPORTATION EQUIPMENT CAN BE INSPECTED ON A MORE FREQUENT, MORE FREQUENT PERIODIC EQUIPMENT INSPECTIONS ARE RECOMMENDED ON EQUIPMENT THAT CONTAIN CORROSIVE MATERIAL. I ALSO RECOMMEND INTERMITTENT INSPECTIONS BY THE DRIVER IN ROUTE TO DESTINATIONS OVER 75 MILES. THIS MAY HELP THE DRIVER DISCOVER A ISSUE WITH HIS EQUIPMENT SOONER THAT MAY REDUCE THE IMPACT LATER DOWN THE LINE.

column168: DRIVER WAS FUELING UP TUG BOATS AT COOK COAL TERMINAL IN METROPOLIS, IL. HE WAS LOADING DIESEL FUEL TO TUG 1 OUT OF A COMPARTMENT ON HIS TRUCK, WHEN HIS COMPARTMENT EMPTIED. THE DRIVER THEN WALKED TO THE CONTROL PANEL ON HIS TRUCK TO SWITCH COMPARTMENTS WHEN THE FIRST COMPARTMENT EMPTIED. AS HE SWITCHED COMPARTMENT THE FUEL HOSE PRESSURIZED AND PUSHED THE FUEL NOZZLE OUT OF THE TUG BOAT TRANSPORT DROP. THE NOZZLE LANDED IN SUCH A WAY, THAT A STREAM OF DYED DIESEL FUEL LANDED ON THE ADJACENT BOAT (TUG 11), AND APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS OF DIESEL LANDED IN THE RIVER. THE MISTAKE WAS DISCOVERED IMMEDIATELY AND WITHIN SECONDS THE DRIVER STOPPED THE FLOW OF FUEL. OUR DRIVER AS WELL AS MEMBERS OF THE TUG CREW UTILIZED BOOMS AND OTHER ABSORBENT MATERIALS TO CAPTURE AND CONTAIN THE DIESEL SPILL. THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS ISOLATED AND CLEANED FROM THE WATER, AND THE FUEL ON THE DECK OF TUG 11 WAS ALSO CLEANED AND REMOVED. THE INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO THE NRC, COAST GUARD AND THE ILLINOIS EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT AGENCY IEMA0. HUMAN ERROR WAS THE SOURCE OF THIS INCIDENT.
column169: SAFETY AND MANAGEMENT PERSONNEL FROM BOTH COOK COAL AND THE RESPONSIBLE PARTY, SOUTHERN FS INC., HAVE MET AND DISCUSSED WAYS OF PREVENTING SITUATIONS LIKE THIS FROM OCCURRING IN THE FUTURE. IT WAS DECIDED THAT SOUTHERN FS’S DRIVERS WOULD RECEIVE TRAINING ON A REFINED FUELING PROCEDURE SPECIFICALLY FORMATTED TO THE DRIVER’S EQUIPMENT. IN ADDITION TO THE INCREASE OF TRAINING, EQUIPMENT UPDATES ARE INTENDED FOR FUTURE DELIVERIES. SOUTHERN FS DRIVERS ARE LOOKING INTO USING RESTRAINING OR “TIE-DOWN” DEVICES THAT WOULD SECURE HOSE NOZZLES TO THE TRANSPORT DROPS, PREVENTING THEM FROM SLIPPING OUT AND CAUSING SPILLS. I WOULD SAY THAT THE USE OF DEVICES. FOR SECURING FUEL HOSE NOZZLES INTO THE FILL TUBES ON TUGS WOULD BE THE EASIEST AND MOST EFFECTIVE MEANS OF REDUCING POTENTIAL SPILLS FOR FUTURE LOADS.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: TIDEWATER TRANSIT WAS TRANSPORTING A TANKER OF SULFURIC ACID. THE TANKER VEHICLE PRESSURIZED, RESULTING IN THE RELEASE OF A SMALL VOLUME (ESTIMATED AT LESS THAN 10 GALLONS) OF SULFURIC ACID TO THE GROUND SURFACE ALONG THE ROADWAY. THE VEHICLE WAS STOPPED BY LOCAL LAW ENFORCEMENT, AND TIDEWATER MANAGEMENT WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT. TIDEWATER MANAGEMENT THEN CONTACTED HIGHLANDS ENVIRONMENTAL SOLUTIONS FOR SPILL RESPONSE SERVICES. RESPONSE ACTIVITIES WERE PERFORMED AND COMPLETED ON THE DATE OF THE INCIDENT. THE RELEASED MATERIAL WAS NEUTRALIZED AND RECOVERED. THE TOP OF THE TANKER THAT CAME IN CONTACT WITH THE ACID WAS CLEANED, AND IT WAS VERIFIED THAT THE TANKER WAS NO LONGER PRESSURIZED AND THE DOME LID WAS SECURED. THE TANKER THEN CONTINUED ENROUTE WITH THE DELIVERY.     AFTER STOPPING THE VEHICLE, A POLICE OFFICER WAS REPORTEDLY EXPOSED TO SULFURIC ACID VAPORS. THE POLICE OFFICER WAS TREATED AND RELEASED.

column168: ON 9/17/17 AT 11:50-PM OUR TRUCK WAS DRIVING NORTH BOUND ON INTERSTATE 81. A VEHICLE MERGED ON FROM THE RIGHT LANE AND RAN INTO THE SIDE OF OUR TRUCK. THE VEHICLE NEVER SLOWED NOR YIELDED TO ON COMING TRAFFIC. THE RESULT OF THE ACCIDENT CAUSED ONE OF THE DRUMS TO SHIFT WHICH RESULTED IN THE CAP POPPING OFF. THE CAP WAS PUT BACK ON DRUM AND TIGHTEN. THE LEAK ON THE FLOOR WAS CLEANED UP WITH SPEEDY DRY AND ABSORBENT PADS. THE SPILL WAS LESS THAN ONE GALLON, IT WAS CONTAINED WITHIN THE TRAILER WHICH IS EQUIPPED WITH A STEEL SPILL FLOOR AND DIKE BOARD. THE CLEANUP CONTRACTOR DATOM PRODUCTS REPORTED THEIR FINDING TO LACKAWANNA EMA. BECAUSE NO ACTIVE RELEASE WAS PRESENT THE TRUCK WAS GIVING PERMISSION TO RETURN TO OUR TERMINAL (2 MILES AWAY) TO CLEANUP SPEEDY DRY AND ABSORBENT PADS. LOAD DELIVERED TO STABLEX WITH NO FURTHER INCIDENT.
column169: PACKAGES NEED TO BE PROPERLY WITHIN VEHICLE AND CAPS, LIDS, AND VALUES NEED TO BE DOUBLE CHECKED TO ASSURE THEY ARE TIGHT.

column168: At approximately 1200 on 09/28/17, the Pittsburgh shuttle arrived to Twinsburg via Dupre, on trailer 61916. While opening the trailer door to begin offloading, the employee noticed a stream of liquid product along the right half of the trailer.  The employee reported the findings and offloading began with the supervision of the management team. A single drum of liquid flammable hazardous waste was identified as the source of the spill and the puncture location was spotted just under the bolt ring on the open top drum. The drum was then placed into a steel overpack and labeled with the appropriate hazardous waste label. The Dupre trailer itself contained less than one gallon of liquid which then was recovered and disposed.  There also was no evidence that any amount of the spill escaped the trailer during transport. The employee continued offloading the remaining waste from the shuttle to ensure no additional drums were identified. No additional drums were spotted and all waste was placed into the 10 day transit area.
column169: Reviewed incident with the Pittsburgh branch and requested that they load drums of waste and orient the drums to keep the bolts on the rings from coming into contact with another drum.

column168: Pallets were double stacked w/o dunnage at 003 when loaded to 333 - should've never been stacked, total weight 4,620#'s and all in paper bags.     Pallets had shifted in transit, driver was unloading the crooked skids and punctured one of the bottom bags with a fork tine due to the uneven pallet (punctured through bottom in between boards on pallet). It was torn due to the freight overhanging the pallets on all sides and was not protected by cardboard, edge protectors, or any other type of protective mechanism inside of the shrink wrap.
column169: This type of freight should never be double stacked.   Also, when this type of product is shipped, it must not overhang the pallet and must stay within the length/width of the pallet's footprint to avoid damage and tearing in transit.
